The account table contains the following columns:

  • account_id: Unique identifier for the account
  • created_time: Date and time when the account was created
  • created_device: Device used to create the account
  • created_platform: Platform used to create the account
  • country_code: Country code of the country where the account was created
  • created_app_store_id: An identifier for the app store which the account was created

Data Validation and Cleaning¶

Looking at total session counts daily, weekly, and monthly. We can see that the daily session count is very volatile but there are interesting strikes and drops that is happening throughout the year. We can see that the weekly session count is more stable and it is increasing in the begeninning of the year and stayin steady for the most part until a noticable drop in September, ending the year wiht lowest session count since the beginning of the year. Monthly session count also shows a similar trend.¶

Top 10 Days for Daily Average Session Duration:¶
  • End of October: The dates 2016-10-29, 2016-10-30, and 2016-10-31 show very high average session durations. These dates align with Halloween, which suggests that special events or themed content may have driven increased engagement.
  • Early July: The dates 2016-07-02 and 2016-07-03 coincide with a weekend and are near the U.S. Independence Day holiday. There could have been special events or promotions encouraging longer play sessions.
  • Late March: The date 2016-03-26 is a Saturday and the day before Easter Sunday. Again, this could be indicative of holiday-related activities within the game.

We see that there is a very high correlation (0.95) between the session_count and session_duration columns. This is a good sign, because this suggests that on days when there are more sessions (higher session counts), those sessions tend to be longer in duration as well, so our users are more engaged with the contents of the game.¶

Now onto the part where we analyze our Daily Active Users (DAU)¶

Our DAU is defined as the number of unique users who played the game on a given day. We can see that the DAU is very volatile and there are clearly trends to be explored here with a lot of spikes and drops throughout the year.¶
In [ ]:
dau = account_date_session_df.groupby('date')['account_id'].nunique()

plt.figure(figsize=(12, 6))
dau.plot(kind='line')
plt.title('Daily Active Users Over Time')
plt.xlabel('Date')
plt.ylabel('DAU')
plt.show()
In the analysis of DAU, we can see that there is a lot of volatility in the previous graph. To address this, I implemented a rolling mean and standard deviation to smooth out the graph which enabled me to see the trends more clearly with a clearer identification of spikes and drops. I picked a window size of 7 because to analyze the spikes and drops in each week more comprehensively since from our previous graph it seems to be indicating there is more activity over weekends. Additionally, I excluded January from the graph since a lot of accounts were signing up in January and it was skewing the graph.¶
In [ ]:
cutoff_date = pd.to_datetime('2016-02-01')
filtered_df = account_date_session_df[account_date_session_df['date'] >= cutoff_date]

dau_filtered = filtered_df.groupby('date')['account_id'].nunique()

window_size = 7  # for a weekly pattern

rolling_mean_filtered = dau_filtered.rolling(window=window_size, center=True).mean()
rolling_std_filtered = dau_filtered.rolling(window=window_size, center=True).std()

spike_threshold_filtered = rolling_mean_filtered + rolling_std_filtered
drop_threshold_filtered = rolling_mean_filtered - rolling_std_filtered

spikes_filtered = dau_filtered[dau_filtered > spike_threshold_filtered]
drops_filtered = dau_filtered[dau_filtered < drop_threshold_filtered]

plt.figure(figsize=(15, 7))

plt.plot(dau_filtered, label='DAU (Filtered)', color='blue')

plt.plot(rolling_mean_filtered, label='Rolling Mean (Filtered)', color='orange')
plt.fill_between(rolling_mean_filtered.index, rolling_mean_filtered - rolling_std_filtered, rolling_mean_filtered + rolling_std_filtered, color='orange', alpha=0.3, label='Rolling Std Dev (Filtered)')

plt.scatter(spikes_filtered.index, spikes_filtered, label='Spikes (Filtered)', color='green')

plt.scatter(drops_filtered.index, drops_filtered, label='Drops (Filtered)', color='red')

plt.title('DAU with Rolling Mean and Standard Deviation (Excluding Initial Dates)')
plt.xlabel('Date')
plt.ylabel('DAU')
plt.legend()
plt.show()
As we can see our analysis does a good job of identifying spikes and drops but it doesn't seem to be identifying every spike and drop throughout the year and to make this analysis more robust we would need to do add a tighter threshold. In the next part I decided to implement a dynamic threshold to see if we can identify more spikes and drops. I defined spikes as values exceeding the rolling mean by 0.7 times the rolling standard deviation and drops as values falling below the mean by the same factor.¶
In [ ]:
rolling_mean = dau.rolling(window=window_size, center=True).mean()
rolling_std = dau.rolling(window=window_size, center=True).std()

upper_threshold = rolling_mean + 0.7 * rolling_std 
lower_threshold = rolling_mean - 0.7 * rolling_std  

spikes = dau[dau > upper_threshold]
drops = dau[dau < lower_threshold]

plt.figure(figsize=(15, 7))
plt.plot(dau, label='DAU', color='blue')
plt.plot(rolling_mean, label='Rolling Mean', color='orange')
plt.fill_between(rolling_mean.index, upper_threshold, lower_threshold, color='orange', alpha=0.2, label='Threshold Range')
plt.scatter(spikes.index, spikes, label='Spikes', color='green')
plt.scatter(drops.index, drops, label='Drops', color='red')
plt.title('DAU with Rolling Mean, SD, and Dynamic Thresholds')
plt.xlabel('Date')
plt.ylabel('DAU')
plt.legend()
plt.show()
As we can see our graph looks way more robust in identifying every significant drop and spike in our data and lastly we need to drop the month of january to be able to have a better look at these trends.¶

Explaratory Data Analysis¶

As always we start off with a quick look at our data to see what we are dealing with. We can see that we have 5 columns with our account_id being the primary key, created_time being the time when the purchase was made, and a package_id_hash which is the identifier for the package that was purchased. We also have iap_price_usd_cents which is the price of the package purchased in usd cents, and a app_store_id which is the identifier for the app store where the purchase was made.¶
- We merge the purchase table with the account table to get the country code for each purchase in a new DataFrame called sales_data.¶
- We convert iap_price_usd_cents to usd dollars by dividing it by 100.¶
- We aggregate the data by country code and sum the total revenue for each country in a new DataFrame called revenue_by_country.¶
- We can see that the top 10 countries by revenue are United States, China, South Korea, Canada, Turkey, Switzerland, France, United Kingdom, Germany, and Colombia.¶
- It is also important to note that these top 10 countries make up 94% of the total revenue.¶
In [ ]:
sales_data = pd.merge(iap_purchase_df, account_df[['account_id', 'country_code']], on='account_id', how='left')

sales_data['iap_price_usd'] = sales_data['iap_price_usd_cents'] / 100

revenue_by_country = sales_data.groupby('country_code')['iap_price_usd'].sum()

top_10_revenue_by_country = revenue_by_country.sort_values(ascending=False).head(10)
print(top_10_revenue_by_country)

total_revenue = revenue_by_country.sum()

print("Top 10 countries account for {:.2f}% of total revenue.".format(top_10_revenue_percentage.sum()))

Report¶

1) Dataset Descriptions¶

The database for analysis contains three tables, each providing unique insights into user behavior and revenue generation for our mobile game throughout the year of 2016. Here is an overview of each table:

account¶

This table serves as the backbone of user-related data, containing profiles for each user. The key attributes include:

  • account_id: The unique identifier for each user.
  • created_time: The timestamp for when the account was created.
  • created_device: The device model used for account creation.
  • created_platform: The operating system of the device (iOS and Android).
  • country_code: The country code representing the user's location at account creation.
  • created_app_store_id: Identifier for the app store through which the account was created.

account_date_session¶

This table tracks the daily engagement of users, with details on the sessions they've played the game. It includes:

  • account_id: The unique identifier correlating to the account table.
  • date: The date of the user's activity.
  • session_count: The total number of sessions the user had on the given date.
  • session_duration_sec: The total duration of the user's sessions in seconds on the given date.

iap_purchase¶

The in-app purchase table records the transactions made by users within the game. It contains:

  • account_id: Linking back to the account table to associate purchases with users.
  • created_time: Timestamp for when the purchase was made.
  • package_id_hash: An anonymized identifier for the purchased item or package.
  • iap_price_usd_cents: The price of the in-app purchase in US cents.
  • app_store_id: Identifier for the app store through which the purchase was made.

2) Daily Acitivity of Users (DAU)¶

*Quoting from my analysis*

Our DAU is defined as the number of unique users who played the game on a given day. We can see that the DAU is very volatile and there are clearly trends to be explored here with a lot of spikes and drops throughout the year. To address this, I implemented a rolling mean and standard deviation to smooth out the graph which enabled me to see the trends more clearly with a clearer identification of spikes and drops. I picked a window size of 7 to analyze the spikes and drops in each week more comprehensively since from our DAU graph there seems to be more activity over weekends. Additionally, I excluded January from the graph since a lot of accounts were signing up in January and it was skewing the graph. My initial analysis did a good job of identifying spikes and drops but it didn't seem to be identifying every spike and drop throughout the year and to make this analysis more robust I would need to add a tighter threshold. In the next part, I decided to implement a dynamic threshold to see if we can identify more spikes and drops. I defined spikes as values exceeding the rolling mean by 0.7 times the rolling standard deviation and drops as values falling below the mean by the same factor. At the end my graph looked way more robust in identifying every significant drop and spike in our data, and here are the findinds from my analysis:

Spikes:¶

  • Weekend Trends:

A significant number of these top spikes occur on weekends (Saturdays and Sundays). I think this is due to the nature of Supercell games being targeted towards a younger audience who are most likely still in school and generally have more free time during the weekends.

  • Summer Months Trends: I observed several spikes during the summer months (June, July, and August). During summer, users might have more leisure time, because of summer holidays for schools and colleges occur during these months.

  • Holiday Season Trends: Late December dates, like 2016-12-24 (Christmas Eve) and 2016-12-25 (Christmas Day), show increased activity, likely due to the holiday season and when Supercell most likely be running special events or promotions.

Drops:¶

  • Weekdays and Non-Holiday Trends: Many of the dates with drops fall on weekdays or periods not associated with major holidays. This pattern suggests that user activity in the game tends to be lower on typical workdays or school days when users might have less free time for gaming.

  • Post-Holiday Trends:

Some dates that show a drop in session counts follow a holiday or special event. For example, 2016-07-05 is right after the U.S. Independence Day holiday, and the drop might indicate a return to routine after the holiday. This trend also reflects a pattern where users are highly active during holidays and then return to normal activity levels afterward.

  • Seasonal Factors:

Certain months, particularly late summer and autumn months (September, October), show more frequent drops. This could be due to seasonal factors such as the start of the academic year or end of vacation periods, which might reduce the amount of time users have for gaming.

3) Sales Analysis¶

After exploring our iap_purchase dataset and merging this Dataframe with the account table to get the country code for each purchase in a new DataFrame called revenue_by_country, we can see that the top 10 countries by revenue are United States, China, South Korea, Canada, Turkey, Switzerland, France, United Kingdom, Germany, and Colombia. It is also important to note that these top 10 countries make up 94% of the total revenue, which is a significant amount. Further analysis can be done with this data which involves grouping the countries into continents or regions according to how Supercell labels theirs.

Let's talk about the geographic variation in ARPU which comes from our findings from the the scatter plot which gives us a visual representation of the relationship between the number of users and ARPU in each market. I used logarithmic scales to make it easier to identify patterns and outliers:

  • High ARPU in Smaller Markets: Some countries with a very small user base (e.g., Colombia, Austria, Switzerland) have extremely high ARPU. This could suggest that although the user base is limited in these countries, the users who are engaged are spending significantly more.
  • Moderate to High ARPU in Key Markets: Countries like the US, Canada, and South Korea, despite having a larger number of users, still maintain a relatively high ARPU. This indicates that these countries are key markets for Supercell, with a large user base and high spending.
  • Lower ARPU in Large Markets: Some countries with a large user base, like China (CN), show lower ARPU. This could be due to a variety of factors, such as lower spending power in these countries or a less engaged user base. It could also not hurt to consider economic factors/restricitons in these regions.
